    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/1XtZi.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 9,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 13,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/13/c-k-young",
                "reputation": 224191,
                "display_name": "C. K. Young",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 17,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1223427172,
            "creation_date": 1223427172,
            "body": "<p><code>Arrays.asList<\/code> cannot be used with arrays of primitives. Use this instead:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Integer[] randomizer = new Integer[] {200,300,212,111,6,2332}; \nCollections.shuffle(Arrays.asList(randomizer));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The same rule applies to most classes in the collections framework, in that you can't use primitive types.<\/p>\n\n<p>The original code (with <code>int[]<\/code>) compiled fine, but did not work as intended, because of the behaviour of the variadic method <code>asList<\/code>: it just makes a one-element list, with the <code>int<\/code> array as its only member.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 180990,
            "question_id": 180979
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/83fd7d4059fec16d3f138f4f351b6423?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 7808,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 13687,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/13687/john-gardner",
                "reputation": 25288,
                "display_name": "John Gardner"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1223427703,
            "creation_date": 1223427703,
            "body": "<p>Chris' answer is correct.<\/p>\n\n<p>As i said in a comment on Chris' answer, your underlying array will change appropriately unless the arraylist needs to grow, and the list creates a new one and copies items into it.<\/p>\n\n<p>You may want to keep a reference to the list and iterate over that after the Arrays.asList call, and not iterate over the array after that, iterate over the List instead.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 181013,
            "question_id": 180979
        }
